===Etymology 1===
Perhaps a corruption of {{m|en|cheer||to salute with cheers}}, taken in an ironical sense; or more probably from {{bor|en|nl|gekscheren||to jeer|lit=to shear the fool}}, from {{m|nl|gek||a fool}} (see {{m|en|geck}}) + {{m|nl|scheren||to shear}} (see {{m|en|shear|pos=v}}).

====Noun====
{{en-noun}}

# A mocking [[remark]] or reflection.
#: {{syn|en|scoff|taunt|flout|jibe|mockery}}
#* '''1711''', [[w:Jonathan Swift|Jonathan Swift]], The Fable of Midas, in ''The Works of Jonathan Swift'', D.D., Vol XII, Sir Walter Scott, ed., Edinburgh: Archibald Constable and Co., 1824, pages 302-5,
#*: Midas, exposed to all their '''jeers''', Had lost his art, and kept his ears.

